# IMP implementation core

The universal "implement an IMP cleanly" workflow. Used by every Claude
agent that takes one improvement from `docs/backlog/improvements.md` and
turns it into a commit on a worktree branch.

This file defines the shared spine. Two wrappers around it specify how the
agent is invoked and where the output goes:

- [`prompt.md`](./prompt.md) — autonomous evolution loop (cron, `/loop`,
  `/schedule`). Adds pre-flight gate, IMP picking from the queue, two-mode
  worktree setup, in-flight status file, on-disk report.
- [`sub-agent-prompt.md`](./sub-agent-prompt.md) — parent-session-driven
  invocation via the Agent tool. Receives the IMP id as a parameter,
  verifies preconditions instead of creating them, returns a structured
  report to the parent in chat.

The wrappers are small. The bulk of the work lives here.

## Hard constraints (always, in any wrapper)

1. **Never commit to `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`.** All work happens on a worktree
   branch.
2. **Never push.** No `git push` under any circumstances.
3. **Never modify strategic decisions** (D1–DN in [`ROADMAP.md`](../../ROADMAP.md)). Those are human-only.
4. **Never touch files outside the chosen IMP's scope.** No drive-by
   refactors, no "while I'm here" cleanups.
5. **Never skip the rubric.** Walk it twice — planning mode before code,
   verification mode after.
6. **Never proceed if `{{TYPE_CHECK_CMD}}` / `{{LINT_CMD}}` / `{{BUILD_CMD}}` fails** at the verification
   stage. Revert the work and write a blocker note instead.
7. **Pick exactly one improvement per invocation.** Resist scope creep.

If any constraint is at risk, stop and write a status note rather than push
through.

## Preconditions the wrapper must establish before calling in

Both wrappers guarantee these before they hand off to the core. The core
re-verifies them as a sanity check at the start of Step A.

- You are in a git worktree (not the main checkout).
- The current branch is not `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`.
- The working tree is clean (`git status --porcelain` is empty).
- A specific `IMP-NNN` has been chosen, and its id is known.
- The IMP's status is sane to start work on: `proposed`, `accepted`,
  `scheduled-phase-N` (where N is the current phase), or `in-progress`.

```bash
# Run this at the top of Step A. Any failure → stop, report to wrapper.
br=$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)
[ "$br" != "{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}" ] || { echo "FAIL: on $br"; exit 1; }
[ -z "$(git status --porcelain)" ] || { echo "FAIL: working tree dirty"; exit 1; }
# (IMP id sanity check is wrapper-specific.)
```

If a sanity check fails, stop and tell the wrapper. Do not try to recover —
the wrapper's environment is the wrapper's problem.

---

## Step A — Read the project's context

Read these in order, fully:

1. [`CLAUDE.md`](../../CLAUDE.md) — project orientation
2. [`ROADMAP.md`](../../ROADMAP.md) — strategic plan, current phase, deliverables
3. Top of [`CHANGELOG.md`](../../CHANGELOG.md) — what's been happening recently (last ~5 entries)
4. The chosen IMP's entry in [`docs/backlog/improvements.md`](../backlog/improvements.md)
5. Any FB / IMP entries cross-referenced from the chosen IMP
6. [`docs/rubric.md`](../rubric.md) — the checklist you'll walk twice

Form a mental model. Identify the **current phase** from ROADMAP. Verify the
chosen IMP's target phase matches. If it doesn't, stop and tell the wrapper —
the wrapper is responsible for picking phase-aligned items.

## Step B — Walk the rubric in PLANNING mode

For every item in [`docs/rubric.md`](../rubric.md) (R1.1 through R10.x), make
one of three decisions for the chosen IMP:

- **handle now** — implement an answer in this change
- **defer** — file a follow-up `IMP-NNN` for later (or note an existing one)
- **wontfix** — explicitly skip with a one-line reason

If many items are deferred or `wontfix`, that's a signal the chosen IMP is
too ambitious. Consider stopping and telling the wrapper that a smaller scope
is needed.

**Where to put the planning rubric:** wrapper's choice.

- Autonomous wrapper writes it to `docs/autorun/reports/<TS>-rubric-plan.md`
  so the human can review it after-the-fact.
- Parent-driven wrapper keeps it in working memory and includes the key
  items in the prose report back to the parent.

The decisions matter, not the file format. Make them concretely; abstract
"I'll keep that in mind" doesn't count.

## Step C — Flip the IMP status to `in-progress`

In [`docs/backlog/improvements.md`](../backlog/improvements.md), change the
chosen `IMP-NNN`'s status from its current value (`proposed` / `accepted` /
`scheduled-phase-N`) to `in-progress`. Add a one-line note:

> *"Started YYYY-MM-DD on branch `<current-branch>`."*

(The branch name encodes which agent took the work — autonomous uses
`autorun/<TS>`; parent-driven uses whatever the harness assigned.)

## Step D — Implement the change

Apply the planned changes. Stay strictly inside the IMP's scope.

- No drive-by refactors.
- No "while I'm here" cleanups.
- If you discover a separate issue, capture it as a new `FB-NNN` (and
  optionally an `IMP-NNN` with status `proposed`) and continue with the
  original IMP. Do not absorb the new issue into the current commit.

Run `{{TYPE_CHECK_CMD}}`, `{{LINT_CMD}}`, `{{BUILD_CMD}}` periodically during work to catch issues early.

## Step E — Verify

Walk the rubric again, this time in **verification mode**. For every item
the planning rubric flagged "handle now": is the answer *true now in the
code*? The check isn't "did I think about it" but "is it true."

If any "handle now" item now fails verification:

- Try to fix it, if cheap.
- Otherwise revert the work (`git restore .`), set the IMP status back to
  its prior value, and tell the wrapper a blocker note. Do not commit.

Run the full check:

```bash
{{TYPE_CHECK_CMD}}
{{LINT_CMD}}
{{BUILD_CMD}}
```

All three must pass. If any fails:

- Try to fix.
- If you can't fix in this run: `git restore .`, set IMP status back, tell
  the wrapper a blocker note. Do **not** commit.

## Step F — Document and commit

Update these files in the worktree (in this order):

1. **`docs/backlog/improvements.md`** — set the IMP's status to `done` and
   link the new CHANGELOG entry.
2. **`docs/decisions/`** — if the change involved a non-obvious decision,
   write an ADR (`NNNN-slug.md`). Use [`docs/decisions/template.md`](../decisions/template.md). Update [`docs/decisions/README.md`](../decisions/README.md) index.
3. **`docs/learning/knowledge-points.md`** — if the change demonstrated a
   transferable concept worth naming, propose one new KP. Skip if nothing
   genuinely general emerged. Quality over quantity — a handful per phase,
   not per commit.
4. **[`CHANGELOG.md`](../../CHANGELOG.md)** — append an entry at the top of
   the current phase, citing rubric items by ID, linking to ADRs / IMPs / FBs.

Stage **specific files** (not `git add .`):

```bash
git add docs/backlog/improvements.md
git add CHANGELOG.md
# add specific source/doc files you changed
git add <each-changed-file>
```

Commit with a message matching the project's existing style. Read recent
commits with `git log --oneline -5` to see the format. End with the
co-author trailer:

```
<short subject line — match recent commit style>

<one-paragraph body explaining what changed and why; reference IMP-NNN>

Closes IMP-NNN. Addresses rubric R-N.N. See ADR-NNNN.

{{COMMIT_TRAILER}}
```

Use a HEREDOC to pass the message so multi-line formatting survives the
shell. After the commit, the worktree branch is the handoff surface — the
wrapper decides what happens next (writes a report file, returns prose to a
parent, etc.).

