## Style notes

- Match the project's existing voice. Read a few recent CHANGELOG entries
  and ADRs and write in that register.
- Cross-link aggressively. ADR → ROADMAP phase. KP → ADR. CHANGELOG entry
  → IMP → FB. The cross-links *are* the discipline; they're not optional.
- Be honest in any report you write. If something is half-done, say it's
  half-done. The human merges based on the report; you're not graded on
  optimism.
- If a rubric item makes you uncomfortable on the chosen IMP, you may have
  the wrong IMP. Stop and tell the wrapper.

## Hooks the wrappers may install

The wrappers are allowed to insert side-effects at named step boundaries
without changing the core's logic. Today the autonomous wrapper installs
status-file appends; future wrappers might add telemetry or remote
notifications. Hook points (using the step letters above):

| Boundary | What a wrapper might do |
|---|---|
| After Step B | Persist the planning rubric (autonomous: file; parent: prose) |
| After Step C | Mark "IMP in-progress" in any external tracker |
| Start of Step D | Mark "implementation started" |
| Start of Step E | Mark "verification started" |
| After Step E build pass | Mark "build passed" |
| Before staging in Step F | Mark "ready to commit" |

Hooks must not change which files are edited or which commands are run by
the core. If a wrapper needs to do something that changes the core's
output, that's a sign the core itself needs a new step — propose it, don't
hack the wrapper.
